<dl id="n42060b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n42" href="#n42060b">N42 (VI.B.31)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n42all.htm#n42060b"> 60(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> mother of the book / (under throne of / God) <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n42060b"><li>FW 50.12 </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/lexc.htm#n42060b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/l39c.htm#n42060b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n42060b">MS BL 47475-23</ms> </li><li>JJA 45:290 <a name="cd8" href="../../ff/fdra/cda.htm#cd8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/c/cd8.htm#n42060b">Draft: I.3&sect;1.8</a>/2.8/3.8</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Mohammad taught that every &ldquo;revelation&rdquo; in the Koran was but a transcript from the pages of a great book, known as the &ldquo;<mark>Mother of the Book</mark>,&rdquo; &ldquo;preserved&rdquo; <mark>under the throne of God</mark>. <small> Stanley Lane-Poole, <a name="SLPS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SLPS"><cite title="source">The Speeches and Table-Talk of the Prophet Mohammad</cite></a> (1882) 186</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
